comments[3]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-05-17T08:39:33.695Z",codex-agent,"Duplicate-check evidence: ran pm context --limit 10; pm search 'pm plan agent planning dependencies related items progressive disclosure' --limit 10; pm search 'pm plan planner planning update_plan claude cursor codex dependencies' --limit 20; pm list-open --fields id,title,status,type,priority,parent,tags --limit 50; pm list-in-progress --limit 20. No existing first-class pm plan command feature was found. Existing pm-planner plugin docs and Codex plugin work are related but not duplicates."
  "2026-05-17T08:40:39.988Z",codex-agent,"Evidence: brainstorming captured in pm-v7dj body/notes/learnings; related items linked: parent pm-rnpb, related pm-0c9q, pm-b7sd, pm-59gj; existing planner docs linked via pm docs. Bootstrap passed: npm install -g ., pm --version 2026.5.14, node v25.9.0, pnpm 10.33.0, pnpm build. No code changes were made."
  "2026-05-17T08:52:52.231Z",codex-agent,"Research and planning evidence 2026-05-17: online sources reviewed for Codex ExecPlans, Codex CLI, Claude Plan Mode/Task tools, Cursor Plan Mode, and Cursor agent best practices. Direction changed from sidecar plan artifact to built-in Plan item type that reuses pm history/search/dependencies. Created child implementation tasks pm-jauk, pm-ze5g, and pm-aqat with linked files/tests and acceptance criteria for future agents."
notes[2]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-05-17T08:39:33.695Z",codex-agent,"Brainstorming source: user requested a pm plan feature comparable to Codex/Claude/Cursor plan surfaces,with easy dependency and related-item linking for agents."
  "2026-05-17T08:40:15.335Z",codex-agent,"Concrete command sketch for `pm plan`:\n- `pm plan create --title \"...\" --scope pm-xxxx --related pm-yyyy --claim --json` creates a durable plan attached to an item or request.\n- `pm plan add-step <PLAN> --text \"...\" --depends-on pm-xxxx --related pm-yyyy --status pending` records a linked step.\n- `pm plan update-step <PLAN> 2 --status in_progress --evidence \"...\"` should enforce a single active step unless `--allow-multiple-active` is passed.\n- `pm plan complete-step <PLAN> 2 --evidence \"tests passed\"` is the harness-equivalent checklist completion mutation.\n- `pm plan show <PLAN> --depth brief|standard|deep --fields id,current_step,linked_items --json` gives progressive-disclosure reads.\n- `pm plan materialize <PLAN> --steps 2,3 --type Task --parent pm-xxxx` converts selected steps into real pm items and links them back with discovered_from/implements relationships.\n\nSuggested JSON shape: `{ id, scope_item_id, title, status, current_step_id, steps:[{id, order, text, status, linked_items:[{id, kind}], evidence, updated_at}], summary:{pending,active,blocked,completed}, next_actions:[...] }`."
learnings[1]{created_at,author,text}:
  "2026-05-17T08:40:26.762Z",codex-agent,"Existing `pm-planner` plugin assets are workflow guidance, not a durable first-class plan artifact. The durable gap is a core/SDK/MCP plan state model that agents can update like harness checklists while linking each step to pm dependencies and related work. Keep the MVP harness-neutral and expose stable JSON so Codex, Claude Code, Cursor, and plugins can adapt it without hardcoding one harness model into core."
docs[2]{path,scope,note}:
  plugins/pm-claude/commands/pm-planner.md,project,existing Claude slash-command planning loop reference
  plugins/pm-claude/skills/pm-planner/SKILL.md,project,existing Claude planner skill reference
body: "Brainstormed design for a first-class `pm plan` command optimized for agent harness planning loops.\n\nProblem framing:\n- Modern harnesses already expose an ephemeral plan surface: Codex update_plan, Claude Code task/todo panels, Cursor-style planning/checklist flows. Those are useful in-session but weak as durable project memory.\n- `pm plan` should bridge that gap: keep the familiar lightweight plan/update loop while storing enough structured links to make plans searchable, resumable, auditable, and connected to pm items.\n- The command should not replace Epics/Features/Tasks. It should be a progressive-disclosure planning artifact that can later materialize, link, or update pm items.\n\nCore product idea:\n- `pm plan create` starts a plan attached to a scope item or ad-hoc request, with optional `--parent`, `--related`, `--blocks`, `--blocked-by`, `--from-search`, and `--claim` helpers.\n- `pm plan add-step` records ordered steps with `pending|in_progress|completed|blocked|skipped` status, owner, confidence, evidence, and optional linked pm IDs.\n- `pm plan update-step` mirrors agent harness plan updates: exactly one active step by default, deterministic reorder/replace semantics, and append-only history entries.\n- `pm plan link` attaches dependencies or related work after discovery without forcing item creation.\n- `pm plan materialize` can turn selected plan steps into pm tasks/features while preserving links back to the source plan.\n- `pm plan show` defaults to brief TOON, with `--depth standard|deep`, `--fields`, `--json`, and `--for-agent` projection modes.\n\nAgent optimization principles:\n- Low-token first: default output should show plan id, scope, current step, blocked steps, linked item IDs, and next command hints; deep detail should be opt-in.\n- Harness-compatible vocabulary: create/update/complete/block steps map directly to Codex update_plan, Claude TodoWrite/TaskCreate, and Cursor plan checklist behavior.\n- Dependency-first flow: every step may link `depends_on`, `related`, `blocks`, `implements`, `verifies`, or `discovered_from` pm IDs.\n- Search-native storage: plan title, summary, step text, linked item titles, evidence comments, and decisions should enter the keyword/semantic corpus.\n- Progressive disclosure: plans can begin as lightweight local session checklists and later gain item links, acceptance criteria, files/tests/docs, or materialized children.\n- Safe automation: every mutation writes history; plan close requires explicit resolution/evidence; linked test/file/doc mutation boundaries remain existing pm commands.\n\nOpen design questions:\n- Storage model: dedicated `plans/pm-plan-*.toon` artifacts versus plan sections embedded on a normal pm item. Dedicated artifacts are cleaner for many ephemeral plans; embedded plans are simpler and inherit item lifecycle.\n- ID model: separate `pl-xxxx` ids versus normal pm item IDs. Separate ids avoid polluting task lists; normal items are easier for existing search/list/deps.\n- Status semantics: whether a completed plan means the plan was executed, or only that the plan was handed off/materialized.\n- UI contract: whether `pm plan` should emit direct harness adapter hints or stay harness-neutral and expose stable JSON for plugins/MCP to translate.\n\nRecommended MVP:\n1. Implement `pm plan create|show|update|add-step|complete-step|block-step|link|close` as a core command family with TOON/JSON output.\n2. Store plans as a typed metadata section on a pm item first, because it reuses existing history, search, ownership, and dependency machinery.\n3. Add `pm plan create --scope <item-id>` and `pm plan link --step <n> --related <id>` so agents can attach discovered context without creating duplicate tasks.\n4. Add `pm plan materialize --steps 2,4 --type Task --parent <id>` after the basic loop is stable.\n5. Add SDK/MCP contracts and plugin commands for Codex/Claude once the CLI contract is stable.\n\n## 2026-05-17 Research Update: Make plans a first-class `Plan` item type\n\nDecision: implement plans as a normal built-in pm item type named `Plan`, with lowercase `plan` accepted through the existing case-insensitive type resolver. This is better than a separate `plans/` artifact model because it reuses item storage, search, dependencies, ownership, comments, notes, learnings, linked files/docs/tests, validation, and history streams immediately.\n\nCurrent repo facts for implementers:\n- Built-in item types currently live in `src/types.ts` as `BUILTIN_ITEM_TYPE_VALUES`.\n- Built-in type folder mapping currently lives in `src/core/shared/constants.ts` as `TYPE_TO_FOLDER`.\n- The runtime type registry already resolves names case-insensitively through `alias_to_type`, so adding `Plan` should make `--type plan` work without a separate lowercase built-in.\n- Settings and extensions can already add item types, but this feature should be core because agent plan mode is a first-class pm workflow, not a package-only optional workflow.\n- `pm contracts --command create --flags-only --json` currently reports no `Plan` type, so implementation must update contracts/help/completion/runtime schema tests.\n\nOnline research summary:\n- Codex guidance for long-running work favors durable living execution plans that are self-contained, include progress, decision logs, validation, and enough context for a stateless future agent to resume.\n- Claude Code Plan Mode is read-only before approval: it reads files and proposes a plan without writing changes until the user approves. Its emerging Task tools split list creation and updates into `TaskCreate`, `TaskUpdate`, `TaskList`, and `TaskGet`, with statuses `pending`, `in_progress`, and `completed`, plus blocked-by/blocks and owner metadata.\n- Cursor Plan Mode researches the codebase, asks clarifying questions, creates editable plans with file paths and code references, supports creating/updating plans, and can save plans as Markdown for future reference. Cursor's agent best-practices guide says planning before coding is the most impactful workflow change and recommends saving plans to make future agent resumption easier.\n\nSource links used for the research:\n- OpenAI Codex PLANS.md / ExecPlan cookbook: https://developers.openai.com/cookbook/articles/codex_exec_plans\n- OpenAI Codex CLI overview: https://developers.openai.com/codex/cli\n- Claude Code common workflows / Plan Mode: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/common-workflows\n- Claude Agent SDK todo/task tracking: https://code.claude.com/docs/en/agent-sdk/todo-tracking\n- Cursor Plan Mode announcement: https://cursor.com/blog/plan-mode\n- Cursor agent best practices: https://cursor.com/blog/agent-best-practices\n\nRequired `Plan` item metadata shape:\n- `plan_mode`: `draft|research|review|approved|executing|paused|completed|superseded` for plan-specific lifecycle while retaining normal item `status`.\n- `plan_scope`: short statement of the target change or investigation.\n- `plan_harness`: optional `codex|claude-code|cursor|generic` provenance.\n- `plan_steps`: ordered list of stable step ids with `title`, `body`, `status`, `owner`, `evidence`, `linked_items`, `files`, `tests`, `docs`, `created_at`, `updated_at`.\n- `plan_decisions`: append-only decision log entries with decision, rationale, source/evidence, author, timestamp.\n- `plan_discoveries`: surprises, risks, unknowns, and codebase findings discovered during read-only planning.\n- `plan_validation`: expected commands, manual checks, and observable outcomes.\n- `plan_resume_context`: compact summary for a future agent after context compaction or a new session.\n\nStep status model:\n- Support `pending`, `in_progress`, `completed`, `blocked`, `skipped`, and `superseded`.\n- Default invariant: one `in_progress` step per Plan item unless `--allow-multiple-active` is explicit for parallel work.\n- Preserve every step mutation through normal pm history entries. Do not rewrite steps in-place outside pm mutation commands.\n\nDependency and relation model:\n- Use existing pm dependencies for item-level relations: `parent`, `child`, `related`, `blocks`, `discovered_from`.\n- Add step-level `linked_items` entries with `id`, `kind`, `note`, and optional `required_before_step` boolean.\n- `pm plan link <PLAN> --step <id|order> --related pm-xxxx` should add a step-level link and optionally a top-level item dependency when `--promote-to-item-dep` is passed.\n- `pm plan materialize` should create normal Tasks/Features from selected steps and add bidirectional `discovered_from`/`child` or `related` links.\n\nCommand MVP:\n- `pm create --type Plan --title ...` should work as a normal item create path.\n- `pm plan create --title ... --scope ... --parent pm-xxxx --related pm-yyyy --from-search \"query\"` should create a `Plan` item with duplicate-check/search evidence.\n- `pm plan show <ID> --depth brief|standard|deep --fields ... --json` should provide progressive disclosure. Brief should show id, title, plan_mode, current step, blockers, linked pm ids, and next suggested command.\n- `pm plan add-step <ID> --title ... --body ... --depends-on pm-xxxx --related pm-yyyy` should append a stable step id.\n- `pm plan update-step <ID> <STEP> --status ... --evidence ...` should patch one step and history-log the mutation.\n- `pm plan complete-step`, `pm plan block-step`, `pm plan reorder-step`, and `pm plan materialize` should be convenience wrappers around the same typed mutation path.\n- SDK/MCP contracts should expose both normal item CRUD support for type `Plan` and dedicated plan actions for harness-native integrations.\n\nOutput requirements:\n- Default TOON output must be low-token and agent-readable.\n- JSON output must include deterministic fields: `item`, `plan`, `current_step`, `steps_summary`, `linked_items`, `next_actions`, and `history_event` or mutation summary.\n- `--fields` must support low-token projections such as `id,title,plan_mode,current_step,blocked_steps,linked_items`.\n- Search corpus must include plan scope, step titles/bodies, decisions, discoveries, validation, dependencies, and linked docs/files/tests.\n\nSafety and history requirements:\n- Plan items must use the same history hash-chain behavior as all other pm items.\n- Every step add/update/reorder/link/materialize mutation must produce a history entry.\n- Read-only planning should be representable without code edits: `plan_mode=research|review` and item `status=open|in_progress` are enough.\n- Approval to execute should be explicit: `pm plan approve <ID>` can set `plan_mode=approved`, while normal implementation claims/status continue through existing item workflow.\n- Closing a Plan item should require evidence of one of: implemented/materialized, superseded by another plan/item, canceled with rationale, or completed as analysis-only.\n\nImplementation touchpoints:\n- `src/types.ts`: add `Plan` to `BUILTIN_ITEM_TYPE_VALUES`.\n- `src/core/shared/constants.ts`: map `Plan` to a `plans` folder and include folder creation/defaults where required.\n- `src/core/item/type-registry.ts`: confirm lowercase alias behavior and add tests that `--type plan` resolves to `Plan`.\n- `src/core/item/item-format.ts` and `src/types.ts`: add typed plan metadata fields if the project chooses strong typing over generic metadata.\n- `src/core/search/corpus.ts` and search command tests: include plan fields in keyword/semantic corpus.\n- `src/cli/commands/create.ts`, `update.ts`, and help/usage surfaces: ensure `Plan` participates in create/update validation without schedule presets.\n- New `src/cli/commands/plan.ts`: dedicated step lifecycle commands.\n- `src/cli/main.ts`, `src/cli/commands/index.ts`, completion, help, contracts, SDK and MCP surfaces: register/discover `pm plan`.\n- Plugins `plugins/pm-claude` and `plugins/pm-codex`: add slash commands/skills once core contracts exist.\n- `scripts/dogfood-package-first.mjs`: add Plan create/show/update/link/materialize smoke coverage.\n\nRecommended child implementation order:\n1. Add built-in `Plan` item type and folder/runtime/schema/search integration.\n2. Add `pm plan` command family with typed step lifecycle mutations and history tests.\n3. Add SDK/MCP/plugin/docs/dogfood coverage and agent-harness examples."
